  see  Harward  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Harward","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Hereward</i>, usually representing Old English <i>Hereweard</i> (from <i>here</i> ‘army’ + <i>weard</i> ‘ward, guardian’) but possibly in some cases the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Hariward</i>, <i>Heriward</i> through Norman introduction. This name was borne by an 11th-century thane of Lincolnshire, leader of resistance to the advancing Normans."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":19,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":28,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":63,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":94,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Hereward was born about 1196, in Booton, Norfolk, England, his father, Robert Hereward, was 38 and his mother, Mrs Robert Howard, was 28. He married Mary Duke before 1224, in Brampton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died before 1296, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1196–before 1296":"umbes 1196–enne 1296","1196–1296":"1196–1296","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1224–1303":"1224–1303","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","bef. 1224":"enne 1224","1296":"1296","1196":"1196","Abt 1224":"umbes 1224","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","before 1296":"enne 1296","about 1196":"umbes 1196","Brampton, Suffolk, England":"Brampton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Frampton, Gloucestershire, England":"Frampton by Cirencester, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Booton, Norfolk, England":"Booton, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1196–before 1296":"noin 1196–ennen vuotta 1296","1196–1296":"1196–1296","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1